{"title_page": "Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies", "text_new": "{{short description|UK governmental advisory body}}\nThe '''Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies''' ('''SAGE''') is a UK governmental advisory body that advises central government in emergencies. It is usually chaired by the UK's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]].<ref name=gov.uk>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage|title=Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies (SAGE)|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2014/uk-response-fukushima-and-anglo-japanese-relations|title=The UK Response to Fukushima and Anglo-Japanese Relations|website=Science & Diplomacy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic, SAGE was criticised for a lack of transparency.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Landler |first1=Mark |last2=Castle |first2=Stephen |title=The Secretive Group Guiding the U.K. on Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/23/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-sage-secret.html |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Although its list of members is not secret (mins of each meeting are taken along with each member involved), [[Chris Whitty]], speaking to the [[Health and Social Care Committee]] regarding the COVID19 gathering of SAGE, said that SAGE was \"given quite clear advice from the [[Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure]] basically based on the fact that SAGE is a sub-committee of [[Cabinet Office Briefing Rooms|Cobra]]\".<ref name=\"indep-sharman-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Sharman |first1=Jon |title=Publishing Sage membership would \u2018increase public confidence\u2019 in government, agrees Whitty |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-sage-evidence-chris-whitty-public-members-a9482941.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> [[Patrick Vallance]] argued in a letter to [[Parliament]] that scientists were protected by the anonymity from \"lobbying and other forms of unwanted influence\".<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\n== Outbreaks and pandemics ==\nSAGE has advised the government on a number of events, including:<ref name=gov.uk/>\n\n* the [[2009 flu pandemic]]\n* the [[2010 eruptions of Eyjafjallaj\u00f6kull]]\n* the 2011 [[Fukushima nuclear accident]]\n* the [[2013\u201314 United Kingdom winter floods]]\n* the [[2014 Ebola outbreak]]\n* the [[2015 Nepal earthquake]]\n* the [[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic]]\n* the potential catastrophic breach of [[Toddbrook reservoir]] in 2019\n* the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== Members during COVID-19 pandemic ==\n{{As of|2020|04}}, during the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], attendees to a meeting of the group included:<ref>{{Cite news|first=Ian |last=Sample|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/coronavirus-whos-who-on-secret-scientific-group-advising-uk-government-sage|title=Who's who on secret scientific group advising UK government?|date=2020-04-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n{{div col}}\nSenior advisers:\n* Sir [[Patrick Vallance]], Chief Scientific Adviser (chair)\n* Professor [[Chris Whitty]], Chief Medical Adviser\n\nMedical and scientific experts:\n* Professor [[John Aston (statistician)|John Aston]], statistician, Chief Scientific Adviser to the Home Office\n* [[Meera Chand (Public Health England)|Meera Chand]], microbiologist\n* Sir [[Ian Diamond]], [[National Statistician]]\n* Professor [[John Edmunds (epidemiologist)|John Edmunds]], epidemiologist\n* Sir [[Jeremy Farrar]], medical researcher\n* Professor [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]], epidemiologist\n* Professor [[Peter Horby]], epidemiologist\n* Professor [[Angela McLean (mathematical biologist)|Angela McLean]], mathematical biologist\n* Professor [[Graham Medley]], epidemiologist\n* Dr [[Edward Mullins]], clinical adviser\n* Professor [[Sharon Peacock]], microbiologist\n* Professor [[Stephen Powis]], national medical director for England\n* Professor [[Andrew Rambaut (molecular biologist)|Andrew Rambaut]], molecular biologist\n* [[Emma Reed (Department of Health and Social Care)|Emma Reed]], emergency planner\n* Professor [[Brooke Rogers]], social psychologist\n* [[James Rubin (psychologist)|James Rubin]], psychologist\n* Professor [[Jonathan Van-Tam]], influenza specialist, Deputy Chief Medical Officer for England\n* Professor [[Charlotte Watts]], epidemiologist, Chief Scientific Advisor to the Department for International Development\n* Professor [[Maria Zambon (scientist)|Maria Zambon]], virologist\n\nDowning Street advisers:\n* [[Dominic Cummings]]<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\">{{cite web |title=Revealed: Cummings is on secret scientific advisory group for Covid-19 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/24/revealed-dominic-cummings-on-secret-scientific-advisory-group-for-covid-19 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Warner (data scientist)|Ben Warner]], data scientist<ref name=\"guardian-sage-covid\"/>\n{{div col end}}\n\nVallance has written that SAGE includes scientists and experts from more than twenty separate institutions. SAGE also contains four expert groups which may each have as low as five and as many as over forty members.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\"/>\n\nDominic Cummings was confirmed by [[Downing Street]] to have attended a 23 March meeting, but the government said Cummings was not a member of SAGE.<ref name=\"bbc-cummings\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Dominic Cummings attended meetings of key scientific group |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52421744 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[COBR]]\n* [[New and Emerging Respiratory Virus Threats Advisory Group]]\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage}}\n\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Emergency management in the United Kingdom]]\n\n\n{{UK-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|UK governmental advisory body}}\nThe '''Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies''' ('''SAGE''') is a UK governmental advisory body that advises central government in emergencies. It is usually chaired by the UK's [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]].<ref name=gov.uk>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/scientific-advisory-group-for-emergencies-sage|title=Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies (SAGE)|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sciencediplomacy.org/perspective/2014/uk-response-fukushima-and-anglo-japanese-relations|title=The UK Response to Fukushima and Anglo-Japanese Relations|website=Science & Diplomacy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2020 COVID19 Pandemic, SAGE was criticised for a lack of transparency.<ref name=\"nyt-landler-castle-sage\">{{cite web |last1=Landler |first1=Mark |last2=Castle |first2=Stephen |title=The Secretive Group Guiding the U.K. on Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/23/world/europe/uk-coronavirus-sage-secret.html |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=25 April 2020 |date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> Although its list of members is not secret (mins of each meeting are taken along with each member involved), [[Chris Whitty]], speaking to the [[Health and Social Care Committee]] regarding the COVID19 gathering of SAGE, said that SAGE was \"given quite clear advice from the [[Centre for